---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import EmailCapture from '../components/EmailCapture.astro';
import AuthorBio from '../components/AuthorBio.astro';
import HeroImage from '../components/HeroImage.astro';
import AffiliateNote from '../components/AffiliateNote.astro';
import questionsHero from '../assets/hero/questions-hero.jpg';

const PUBLISH_DATE = '2026-07-11';
const dateFormatter = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' });

const TITLE = '10 Questions to Ask Before You Book a Tea Ceremony in Tokyo (2026)';
const DESCRIPTION = "Before booking a Tokyo tea ceremony, ask about seating, what's included, solo pricing, group size, and tea room vs studio — the questions behind every bad review, answered.";

const questions = [
  {
    question: 'Are chairs available — and do I need to request them?',
    answer: "Only 4 of 18 Tokyo venues publicly confirm chairs, but most can arrange them if you ask at booking, not on arrival.",
  },
  {
    question: 'What exactly is included in the price?',
    answer: '"Tea ceremony" can mean one bowl of matcha and a sweet, or kimono dressing, hair styling, sweets-making, and photos — ask for the inclusion list before comparing prices.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is there a solo surcharge?',
    answer: 'At least one Tokyo venue charges solo guests double the per-person group rate for the same seat — ask before anything else if traveling alone.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How many guests will be in my session?',
    answer: '20-person sessions feel like a demonstration, 8-10 feels like a gathering, private feels like a lesson.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is the venue an actual tea room — or a studio?',
    answer: 'Both can be enjoyable, but they are different products — ask whether the session is held in a traditional tea room.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Who performs the ceremony?',
    answer: '"Tea master" is a marketing word, not a credential — ask whether the host actively practices tea, and in which school.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I take photos — and when?',
    answer: 'Almost always yes, but timing matters: mid-temae photography versus a dedicated photo time at the end are very different asks.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much talking is welcome?',
    answer: 'Sessions range from lecture-style to conversational — ask which way the venue leans if that matters to you.',
  },
  {
    question: "What's the cancellation policy?",
    answer: "Cancellation windows vary widely between booking platforms and direct bookings — know before you pay, especially for private sessions.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Is this a tea ceremony — or a matcha tasting?',
    answer: 'Not the same thing: a tasting serves you tea, a ceremony is a hosted ritual with etiquette, seasonality, and intent.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title={TITLE}
  description={DESCRIPTION}
  ogType="article"
  ogImage={questionsHero}
  showCompareCta
>
  <HeroImage
    src={questionsHero}
    alt="A tokonoma alcove with a hanging scroll reading ichi-go ichi-e beside an ikebana flower arrangement, in a traditional tatami tea room"
  />

  <p class="text-sm text-warm-gray-mid mb-2">
    <time datetime={PUBLISH_DATE}>{dateFormatter.format(new Date(PUBLISH_DATE))}</time>
  </p>
  <AffiliateNote />

  <h1 class="font-serif font-semibold text-4xl text-sumi mb-4 leading-tight">
    10 Questions to Ask Before You Book a Tea Ceremony in Tokyo
  </h1>

  {/* GEO answer block */}
  <div class="bg-sakura-light rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 border-l-4 border-sakura-deep">
    <p class="text-sm font-medium text-sakura-deep mb-1">Quick Answer</p>
    <p class="text-sumi leading-relaxed text-sm">
      Before booking any Tokyo tea ceremony, confirm: seating (chairs or seiza?), what's actually
      included, solo pricing, group size, and whether you're booking a tea room or a studio. Most
      disappointments we hear about trace back to one of these ten questions nobody asked. All ten
      below — with what a good answer sounds like, based on data from all 18 venues in our
      <a href="/tokyo-tea-ceremony-price-index">Tokyo Tea Ceremony Price Index</a>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none text-sumi">
    <p>
      I've reviewed every bookable tea ceremony in Tokyo, and here's the pattern behind bad
      reviews: the venue rarely lied — the guest just didn't know what to ask. So ask these. Any
      venue worth your money will answer happily; hesitation is itself an answer.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Are chairs available — and do I need to request them?</h2>
    <p>
      Only 4 of 18 Tokyo venues publicly confirm chairs, but most can arrange them
      <strong>if you ask at booking, not on arrival</strong>. If seiza is a concern, this is
      question one. (Full details in our
      <a href="/tea-ceremony-without-seiza">seiza-free guide</a>.)
    </p>

    <h2>2. What exactly is included in the price?</h2>
    <p>
      "Tea ceremony" can mean one bowl of matcha and a sweet — or kimono dressing, hair styling,
      sweets-making, and photos. At Maikoya, ¥6,300 includes kimono and hair styling; elsewhere,
      kimono is a paid add-on or not offered. Ask for the inclusion list before comparing prices,
      or you're comparing apples to kettles.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Is there a solo surcharge?</h2>
    <p>
      The quiet trap in Tokyo tea pricing: at least one venue charges solo guests ¥11,000 versus
      ¥5,500 per person for two or more — double, for the same seat. If you're traveling alone,
      ask "is the per-person price the same for one guest?" before anything else.
    </p>

    <h2>4. How many guests will be in my session?</h2>
    <p>
      The answer changes the entire experience: 20-person sessions feel like a demonstration,
      8-10 feels like a gathering, private feels like a lesson. Small-group caps (like
      Jugetsudo's 10) give you most of private's calm at group prices. (More in
      <a href="/private-vs-group-tea-ceremony-tokyo">Private vs Group</a>.)
    </p>

    <h2>5. Is the venue an actual tea room — or a studio?</h2>
    <p>
      Both can be enjoyable; they are different products. A purpose-built tea room (Chazen has a
      tsukubai water basin and nijiriguchi crawl-through entrance) engages the architecture of tea
      itself. A sixth-floor studio with tatami mats is an event space with props. Ask "is the
      session held in a traditional tea room?" — a confident venue will tell you exactly what the
      space is.
    </p>

    <h2>6. Who performs the ceremony?</h2>
    <p>
      "Tea master" is a marketing word, not a credential. What you can ask instead: does the host
      actively practice tea, and in which school (Urasenke, Omotesenke...)? Venues with real
      practitioners tend to say so proudly. A vague answer usually means trained staff performing
      a script — fine for a casual visit, worth knowing in advance.
    </p>
    <p>
      A practitioner's tell: ask which school, and listen to the speed of the answer. Someone who
      actually practices will name their school — Urasenke, Omotesenke — without a beat, the way
      you'd name your hometown. If the answer wanders into "traditional Japanese style" territory
      instead of a school name, you've learned what you needed to know.
    </p>

    <h2>7. Can I take photos — and when?</h2>
    <p>
      Almost always yes, but timing matters: photographing mid-temae (during the tea preparation)
      versus a dedicated photo time at the end are very different asks. Venues that plan photo
      time into the session (many do) will tell you. Asking in advance means you relax instead of
      sneaking shots.
    </p>

    <h2>8. How much talking is welcome?</h2>
    <p>
      Sessions range from lecture-style (listen, then Q&amp;A) to conversational. Questions about
      the utensils, sweets, and season are welcome almost everywhere — that's the good kind of
      talking. What varies is casual chatting; when unsure, let the host set the tone. If a lively
      session matters to you (or a silent one), ask which way the venue leans.
    </p>

    <h2>9. What's the cancellation policy?</h2>
    <p>
      Tokyo experience cancellation windows vary — 24 hours' free cancellation is common on
      booking platforms, direct bookings vary widely. Trip plans change; know before you pay,
      especially for private sessions where you're reserving the whole room.
    </p>

    <h2>10. Is this a tea ceremony — or a matcha tasting?</h2>
    <p>
      Not the same thing, and both exist on booking sites under similar names. A tasting serves
      you tea (sometimes several kinds); a ceremony is a hosted ritual with etiquette, seasonality,
      and intent. Neither is wrong — but reviews saying "not what I expected" are almost always
      this question, unasked. One line to the venue clears it up.
    </p>

    <h2>The meta-question</h2>
    <p>
      If reading these ten feels like homework, here's the shortcut: we've already asked them.
      Every venue in our <a href="/tokyo-tea-ceremony-compared">comparison table</a> is checked
      against seating, inclusions, solo pricing, group size, and setting — with an honest
      practitioner rating on each.
    </p>
    <p>
      And if you're ever unsure whether a question is "allowed": it is. In tea, a guest who cares
      enough to ask is already being a good guest.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="mt-8 text-sm text-sumi/70 border-t border-warm-gray pt-6">
    <p>
      Data from the <a href="/tokyo-tea-ceremony-price-index" class="text-matcha underline">Tokyo Tea Ceremony Price Index</a>,
      checked July 2026, updated quarterly.
    </p>
  </div>

  <EmailCapture />
  <AuthorBio />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Article',
    'headline': TITLE,
    'description': DESCRIPTION,
    'datePublished': PUBLISH_DATE,
    'author': {
      '@type': 'Person',
      'name': 'Suzu',
      'url': 'https://tokyoinseason.com/about',
    },
    'publisher': {
      '@type': 'Organization',
      'name': 'Tokyo in Season',
      'url': 'https://tokyoinseason.com',
    },
    'mainEntityOfPage': 'https://tokyoinseason.com/questions-before-booking-tea-ceremony-tokyo',
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'ItemList',
    'name': '10 Questions to Ask Before You Book a Tea Ceremony in Tokyo',
    'itemListElement': questions.map((q, i) => ({
      '@type': 'ListItem',
      'position': i + 1,
      'name': q.question,
      'item': {
        '@type': 'Question',
        'name': q.question,
        'acceptedAnswer': {
          '@type': 'Answer',
          'text': q.answer,
        },
      },
    })),
  })} />
</BaseLayout>
